<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n19070b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n19" href="#n19070b">N19 (VI.B.19)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n19all.htm#n19070b"> 70(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> gobble him up / (love)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The wolf man&apos;s]</font> fear of his father was the strongest motive for his falling ill, and his ambivalent attitude towards every father-surrogate was the doiminating feature of his life as well as of his behaviour during the treatment. If in my patient&apos;s case the wolf was merely a first father-surrogate, the question arises whether the hidden content in the fairy tales of the wolf that ate up the little goats and of &lsquo;Little Red Riding-Hood&rsquo; may not simply be infantile fear of the father. Moreover. my patient&apos;s father had the characteristic shown by so many people in relation to their children, of indulging in &ldquo;<i>affectionate abuse</i>&rdquo;; and it is possible that during the patient&apos;s earlier years his father &hellip; may more than once, as he caressed the little boy or played with him, have threatened in fun to &lsquo;<mark>gobble him up</mark>&rsquo; <small> Sigmund Freud, <a name="SFWM2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SFWM2"><cite title="source">&ldquo;From the History of an Infantile Neurosis (The &lsquo;Wolf Man&rsquo;)&rdquo;</cite></a> (1925) 502</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
